<DOC><DOCNO> AP880627-0132 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2015EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Olympics     06-27 0369</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea-Olympics,0381</SECOND><HEAD>Korean Police to Use Electric Cattle Prods As Riot Gear</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police will use electric cattle prods,tear gas guns and other anti-riot measures to control demonstratorsand ensure the safety of the Seoul Olympics, police and newsreports said Monday.   Home Minister Lee Choon-ku, in charge of the country's135,000-member police force, ordered an extensive crackdown oncriminals and political radicals before the Olympics, police said.   The former army general urged riot troops to be ``aggressive andoffensive'' and arrest all violent demonstrators, police said.   Newspapers said Lee is giving police permission to use electriccattle prods, gas guns and riot clubs against demonstrators, inaddition to tear gas.   Security has emerged as a major concern for the Olympics, whichrun from Sept. 17 to Oct. 2.   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent student protestsand labor unrest in recent months. So far this year, more than960,000 people took part in about 4,300 mostly anti-governmentdemonstrations, up 80 percent from the same period last year.   Some radical students, who have supported North Korea's demandto be a co-host for the Games, have also staged demonstrationsagainst the Olympics.   North Korea announced it will boycott the Olympics after SouthKorea rejected its demand. North Korea charges that the Olympics inSeoul would prolong the partition of the Korean peninsula.   The two Koreas, divided since the end of World War II, arebitter foes. The two nations fought the bloody Korean War from 1950to 1953 after the North invaded the South.   South Korea, the United States and other nations have expressedconcern that North Korea will try to disrupt the Olympics or thatinternational terrorist groups may stage attacks.   Security officials from seven nations and 13 airlines will meetthis week to plan anti-terrorist measures for the Olympics, theForeign Ministry said today.   The United States, Japan, the Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia,Singapore, and South Korea will attend the meeting, officials said.Hong Kong, a British colony, also plans to send delegates.   Thirteen airlines that fly to Seoul will also discuss ways toensure security for their aircraft during the Olympics, officialssaid. The airlines were not identified.</TEXT></DOC>